{"entryType":"UniProtKB reviewed (Swiss-Prot)","primaryAccession":"P03155","uniProtkbId":"DPOL_HBVD1","entryAudit":{"firstPublicDate":"1986-07-21","lastAnnotationUpdateDate":"2023-02-22","lastSequenceUpdateDate":"1986-07-21","entryVersion":95,"sequenceVersion":1},"annotationScore":5.0,"organism":{"scientificName":"Hepatitis B virus genotype D subtype adw (isolate United Kingdom/adyw/1979)","commonName":"HBV-D","taxonId":10419,"lineage":["Viruses","Riboviria","Pararnavirae","Artverviricota","Revtraviricetes","Blubervirales","Hepadnaviridae","Orthohepadnavirus"]},"organismHosts":[{"scientificName":"Homo sapiens","commonName":"Human","taxonId":9606},{"scientificName":"Pan troglodytes","commonName":"Chimpanzee","taxonId":9598}],"proteinExistence":"1: Evidence at protein level","proteinDescription":{"recommendedName":{"fullName":{"value":"Protein P"}},"includes":[{"recommendedName":{"fullName":{"value":"DNA-directed DNA polymerase"},"ecNumbers":[{"value":"2.7.7.7"}]}},{"recommendedName":{"fullName":{"value":"RNA-directed DNA polymerase"},"ecNumbers":[{"value":"2.7.7.49"}]}},{"recommendedName":{"fullName":{"value":"Ribonuclease H"},"ecNumbers":[{"value":"3.1.26.4"}]}}],"flag":"Fragment"},"genes":[{"geneName":{"value":"P"}}],"comments":[{"texts":[{"evidences":[{"evidenceCode":"ECO:0000250"},{"evidenceCode":"ECO:0000269","source":"PubMed","id":"1380455"},{"evidenceCode":"ECO:0000269","source":"PubMed","id":"2854056"}],"value":"Multifunctional enzyme that converts the viral RNA genome into dsDNA in viral cytoplasmic capsids. This enzyme displays a DNA polymerase activity that can copy either DNA or RNA templates, and a ribonuclease H (RNase H) activity that cleaves the RNA strand of RNA-DNA heteroduplexes in a partially processive 3'- to 5'-endonucleasic mode. Neo-synthesized pregenomic RNA (pgRNA) are encapsidated together with the P protein, and reverse-transcribed inside the nucleocapsid. Initiation of reverse-transcription occurs first by binding the epsilon loop on the pgRNA genome, and is initiated by protein priming, thereby the 5'-end of (-)DNA is covalently linked to P protein. Partial (+)DNA is synthesized from the (-)DNA template and generates the relaxed circular DNA (RC-DNA) genome. After budding and infection, the RC-DNA migrates in the nucleus, and is converted into a plasmid-like covalently closed circular DNA (cccDNA). The activity of P protein does not seem to be necessary for cccDNA generation, and is presumably released from (+)DNA by host nuclear DNA repair machinery (By similarity)"}],"commentType":"FUNCTION"},{"commentType":"CATALYTIC ACTIVITY","reaction":{"name":"a 2'-deoxyribonucleoside 5'-triphosphate + DNA(n) = diphosphate + DNA(n+1)","reactionCrossReferences":[{"database":"Rhea","id":"RHEA:22508"},{"database":"Rhea","id":"RHEA-COMP:17339"},{"database":"Rhea","id":"RHEA-COMP:17340"},{"database":"ChEBI","id":"CHEBI:33019"},{"database":"ChEBI","id":"CHEBI:61560"},{"database":"ChEBI","id":"CHEBI:173112"}],"ecNumber":"2.7.7.7","evidences":[{"evidenceCode":"ECO:0000255","source":"PROSITE-ProRule","id":"PRU00405"}]}},{"commentType":"CATALYTIC ACTIVITY","reaction":{"name":"a 2'-deoxyribonucleoside 5'-triphosphate + DNA(n) = diphosphate + DNA(n+1)","reactionCrossReferences":[{"database":"Rhea","id":"RHEA:22508"},{"database":"Rhea","id":"RHEA-COMP:17339"},{"database":"Rhea","id":"RHEA-COMP:17340"},{"database":"ChEBI","id":"CHEBI:33019"},{"database":"ChEBI","id":"CHEBI:61560"},{"database":"ChEBI","id":"CHEBI:173112"}],"ecNumber":"2.7.7.49","evidences":[{"evidenceCode":"ECO:0000255","source":"PROSITE-ProRule","id":"PRU00405"}]}},{"commentType":"CATALYTIC ACTIVITY","reaction":{"name":"Endonucleolytic cleavage to 5'-phosphomonoester.","ecNumber":"3.1.26.4"}},{"texts":[{"evidences":[{"evidenceCode":"ECO:0000250"}],"value":"Activated by host HSP70 and HSP40 in vitro to be able to bind the epsilon loop of the pgRNA. Because deletion of the RNase H region renders the protein partly chaperone-independent, the chaperones may be needed indirectly to relieve occlusion of the RNA-binding site by this domain. Inhibited by several reverse-transcriptase inhibitors: Lamivudine, Adefovir and Entecavir (By similarity)"}],"commentType":"ACTIVITY REGULATION"},{"texts":[{"evidences":[{"evidenceCode":"ECO:0000250"}],"value":"Terminal protein domain (TP) is hepadnavirus-specific. Spacer domain is highly variable and separates the TP and RT domains. Polymerase/reverse-transcriptase domain (RT) and ribonuclease H domain (RH) are similar to retrovirus reverse transcriptase/RNase H (By similarity)"}],"commentType":"DOMAIN"},{"texts":[{"evidences":[{"evidenceCode":"ECO:0000250"}],"value":"The polymerase/reverse transcriptase (RT) and ribonuclease H (RH) domains are structured in five subdomains: finger, palm, thumb, connection and RNase H. Within the palm subdomain, the 'primer grip' region is thought to be involved in the positioning of the primer terminus for accommodating the incoming nucleotide. The RH domain stabilizes the association of RT with primer-template (By similarity)"}],"commentType":"DOMAIN"},{"texts":[{"evidences":[{"evidenceCode":"ECO:0000250"}],"value":"Hepadnaviral virions contain probably just one P protein molecule per particle"}],"commentType":"MISCELLANEOUS"},{"texts":[{"evidences":[{"evidenceCode":"ECO:0000305"}],"value":"Belongs to the hepadnaviridae P protein family"}],"commentType":"SIMILARITY"}],"features":[{"type":"Chain","location":{"start":{"value":1,"modifier":"EXACT"},"end":{"value":750,"modifier":"OUTSIDE"}},"description":"Protein P","featureId":"PRO_0000222345"},{"type":"Domain","location":{"start":{"value":346,"modifier":"EXACT"},"end":{"value":589,"modifier":"EXACT"}},"description":"Reverse transcriptase","evidences":[{"evidenceCode":"ECO:0000255","source":"PROSITE-ProRule","id":"PRU00405"}]},{"type":"Region","location":{"start":{"value":1,"modifier":"EXACT"},"end":{"value":177,"modifier":"EXACT"}},"description":"Terminal protein domain (TP)","evidences":[{"evidenceCode